 <br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>What is staying the same:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
 <br>
•&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp How status is viewd in the game from a player standpoint.<br>
•&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp How temporary status works in attacks, loans, etc.<br>
•&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp How Permanent status is represented in the game.<br>
•&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The amount of status someone is given in the game for officer positions.<br>
 <br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>What would be changing:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
 <br>
•&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp What status titles are given with offices.<br>
•&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp How status is given out/determined.<br>
•&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Status as a more accurate reflection of a person’s actual reputation or outward appearance.<br>
•&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Addition of negative status traits.<br>
 <br>
Many people have complained that status doesn’t really mean much. The primary reason for this that the status traits really don’t reflect how people feel about that character. Not all Primogen are revered and not all Seneschals are cherished. So why play a trait that really isn’t a part of your character? Kirstin and I have worked really hard to start revising status lto more accurately reflect the way people actually may feel about certain people.<br>
 <br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>What is a negative status trait?</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
 <br>
This is a status trait that reflects you doing something unpopular. It is actually a permanent status trait that can only be lost through work and redeeming yourself. Its impact is fairly profound however. Every negative status trait you have reduces your temporary status pool by that amount. So for example, if you are Acknowledged, (Hated), you essentially have no status to attack, lend, or do anything with. You are still technically acknowledged, but your Hated flaw makes it kind of worthless in many people’s eyes. Similarly, Bob the Vampire has Revered, Powerful, Connected, Untrusted. He’s still very powerful, but he only acts at 2 temporary status traits instead of 3. So yes, it is possible to attack a powerful Kindred by keeping their permanent status intact, but reducing their status power, but giving them a bad rep and assigning negative status traits.<br>
 <br>
This is how you get a leader who is appears powerful, but actually has little power because of reputation. This is how a paper prince would be – someone who had no power. If Marie for example got 4 negative status traits stacked against her, she would be ineffective in setting status. At this point she would have no choice but to relinquish her position on the status council, perhaps, to show her voice no longer has any power.<br>
 <br>
Otherwise, status bidding and temporary, permanent status still works the same as it currently does in the game. Negative traits do affect your pool however.<br>
 <br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>So how is office with status going to change?</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
 <br>
Not in a terribly complex way. When you attain an office in the city, you simply gain the same number of status traits you do now, but you gain them in personalized adjectives that apply directly to your character’s methods, motives, and outward appearance. For example, Grifon attains the post of Senschal. He should normally get the “Cherished” and “Esteemed” status trait, right? Well, those really don’t reflect Grifon’s manners or how people view him. Instead, its decided that Grifon will get the “Feared” and “Efficient” traits instead so that its more reflective of how people view him.<br>
 <br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>How would status be determined differently?</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
 <br>
Well, we know we already have the harpies in place. Towards this end, once a month the Harpy PCs will chair a “Status Council”. The Status Council consists of all the city’s officers, plus the Prince, plus the Harpies themselves. This is a semi-OOC council that accurately reflects the feelings of those with status. The Prince and the Harpies both bring separate lists to the Council, of Kindred they wish to assign negative or positive status to. Similarly, those lists include any status they believe deserves to be stripped due to recent activities that Kindred may have done. Each change is addressed in turn, and then voted on by the members of the council – yes or no. Every member of the Council has 1 vote, save the Prince, who has 2. Similarly, in events where the same Kindred has been recommended for a certain status, the Prince is the final arbiter of which status is assigned. A kindred may never acquire more than 1 negative or 1 positive status trait per status council under normal circumstances.<br>
 <br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Examples:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
 <br>
Estelle and Keith bring their lists to the status council. Marie also has her list. The meeting begins with the Prince going first. She suggests that Cybel, the Nosferatu be given the positive “Adored” trait. She states her reasons for it and then the vote is cast. Estelle, Keith, Alia, and Trevor all vote “no” because they think its not reflective of how the city views her. Prophet, Marie, and Grifon vote “yes”. It’s a tie. The Prince breaks all ties, UNLESS both harpies agree to a certain vote opposite hers. In this case, Keith and Estelle both agreed “No” so the motion doesn’t pass.<br>
 <br>
However, lets say for example that Keith and Estelle both had Cybel down on their list to get the positive status trait “Helpful”. Well, in this case, the vote comes up to simply “award Cybel status”. If the vote passes, then the Prince chooses which status Cybel gets and the Prince decides “Adored”.<br>
 <br>
If someone is awarded positive status, they cannot be awarded negative status in the same council. Negative status is counted as either the removal of a current status trait or the addition of a negative status trait to a person’s sheet. The Primogen’s votes are not counted in the council primarily because they are supposed to influence status through the Harpies and the Harpies are permitted to sit in by the strength of the Primogen’s backing.<br>
 <br>
An individual can vote in their own status raising or lowering if they sit on the Council. This would make it more difficult for someone to simply railroad a powerful, respected individual’s status. Members of the Council are only allowed to cast their votes and make their suggestions for raises and lowers. All debate and Roleplay surrounding the creation of the lists should actually go on prior to the Status Council casting their votes on the matter.<br>
 <br>
So long as the officers of the city retain their position they can never lose the status trait(s) they acquired when attaining that position though they can attain a number of negative traits to make their word in the city all but ineffective. So if you want to discredit someone, attack them with negative traits! A suggestion can be made to change that status trait to something else, so long as the status trait still reflects the power of the office. Lets say for example Grifon goes soft-hearted all of a sudden, and well, the Feared trait doesn’t really apply to him anymore. Marie can suggest “Benevolent” perhaps instead and this change is made in the Status Council. The powers of the Prince on the Status Council are outlined below.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>How will status council work?</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
To speed things up, status council will be done in the form of a ballot. At the end of the night on the 4th week of the month, the harpies and the Prince will exchange their list of status raises/lowers/changes. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>NOTE: If the harpies do not submit their list that night or during the next week, the Prince will simply name her list and she alone will be dictating the status of the populace. At this point the populace needs to take note that the harpies aren’t doing their job and well, this might anger some people who want a voice in status, right? This is the harpies responsibility and if they fail it, they will probably be removed.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The prince will take a week to compile this list into a ballot and on the 1st Friday of the month distribute it to the voters, who will cast their vote, yes or no and turn the ballots in. The 2nd Friday of the month at the start of game, status changes will be announced and people have 3 weeks to RP on those changes or attempt to get them modified. On /rare/ occasions the status council may meet personally in a semi-OOC fashion to discuss things.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>What powers does the Prince retain over status?</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The Prince still retains the power to add or remove the “acknowledged” status from a Kindred at any time. The Prince can also offer “bounty status” as a reward for distinguished service or particular dedication. Bounty status counts against positive status for the month, but cannot be refuted in Status Council unless some evidence arises to contradict that individual’s heroic or distinguished actions. The Prince determines what makes “bounty status”, and if its frivolous things, then no doubt his/her status could be attacked and a negative trait assigned that would make assigning that status more difficult.<br>
<br>
The Prince’s permanent status is iron-clad. Because cities in the Camarilla need and require a strong leader, vampire society itself very rarely seeks to make a weak leader. However, an unpopular Prince may begin to find their power over the city undermined by a series of negative traits.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Example:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Samuel is considered to be Famous, Well-Known, Commanding, and Just. However, he begins to grow unpopular with the people and the populace (through the harpies) attacks his status by saying that he’s getting a bit too aloof. So he earns the negative trait “Aloof” if enough agree that is the case. This could go on to the point where Samuel has no effective status left and he is removed from the Council entirely. At this point the city’s status is in the hands of the officers and the harpies (the populace) and things can degrade even further from there for Sam.<br>
<br>
The Prince’s status is also influenced heavily by the status of the Camarilla. For excellent service as a Prince, many Camarilla Princes are awarded much status and acclaim, and thereby power. The more respected you are the more likely you are to receive help, advice, and favors from other cities.<br>
