The main problem with status is how to balance the OOC and IC aspects of it.  What part of it should be played out and what part of it do folks dicker and dither about out of character.<br>
<br>
Ideally, status should be something that characters reflexively react to, the same as &quot;eerie presence&quot; or &quot;gorgeous&quot;, yes the player may need to announce it, but *characters* should not be quite so consciously aware that it is a currency that can be bought sold and traded.  A character may feel that they deserve more respect, but they shouldn't know that they have been assigned a *trait*.  A character may be completely unaware in game that they are considered &quot;cherished&quot; by the population, until everyone in game comes to their defense when they are in trouble.<br>
This may seem a little confusing to people.<br>
But what it comes down to is how people play the *character*.<br>
The combination of motivations, concept, merits and flaws should build a personality and entity that illicits a certain response from other characters.<br>
This is what makes the difference between LARP and table-top... the potential to explore these interactions and responses.<br>
Coming up with a way to balance this ideal and the actual practical application of game mechanics is a work in progress.<br>
John and Kirie have come up with some good ideas. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bscbnforum58570.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nesuril>Nesuril</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#FF9300>(2/21/03 3:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fscbnforum58570frm16.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=21.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Status Revisions (Suggestions)</span><hr size=1> Agree one hundred percent with you there Marisa about how status needs to be a complete picture of a character and that is an extension of how the player plays it. Your character could be the most competent and wise character on paper, but if you play him like a fool, expect people to regard him with that status. Ideally status should be an extension of RP alone and not attributes on a sheet. One of the things Kirstin and I attempted to do was to &quot;humanize&quot; the status system and put it in terms that were more directly related to the way people play, rather than some obscure term like &quot;Revered&quot;. For example, Keith is a very &quot;Suave&quot; character. That's a positive trait and its reflective of Ken's RP style with that character.<br>
<br>
I think by getting people more into a humanized status system, that process will eventually grow into the kind of &quot;thoughtless&quot; status that Marisa has described. The fact is, status has for a long time been a kind of nebulous entity in the Santa Carla LARP. Some people have abused it for their own gain and even powergamed with status (from rumors). People should learn to have fun with a system of status and the status system should reflect actual RP goings-on rather than projected super-heroic images of characters that aren't RP'd out. I hope this suggestion will try to bring to the fore-front aspects of characters that people maybe are overlooking and should or should not play either for or against those characters. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F9FBFD><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bscbnforum58570.showUserPublicProfile?gid=antoineleblanc@scbnforum58570>Antoine leblanc</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#FF9300>(2/21/03 6:06 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fscbnforum58570frm16.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=21.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Status Revisions (Suggestions)</span><hr size=1> you call a judge &quot;Your Honor&quot; even if the judge isn't honorable.  In my opinion, it's a  title, as is officer status.  I don't see any other problems that your system covers that the books status system doesn't.  <br>
