<br>
1. And I think this should always be the first thing a person thinks of when they think about status: Prestation. Status determines the worth of the currency that is prestation. If John Q. Brujah who just rolled in last week wants a favor from Justicar Ba'Dass with 7 accounts of Feared, John might have to exchange a Major or Blood Boon for even a Minor Boon (but probably not a trivial, depending on negotiations, etc.). This works the other way around, John Q. might be expected to dish out something major in exchange for something not so big.<br>
<br>
2. Status is not what Kindred actually think of each other. If that were the case, they would all think of each other as ravening beasts out to destroy each other, because that's what most of them, especially the Elders with the most status are. Instead, it is the force of vampiric society: a person plays the game, gets boons and if they blackmail the right people, they will eventually get status.<br>
<br>
3. I don't recommend using the negative status trait system. It's been used in this game before and it only makes things more complicated without really adding anything. I recommend just stripping people of status. If you want a paper prince, I suggest simply making it appear like what they are saying is being carried out, and find an alternate way of actually exerting power as opposed to relying on the status system.<br>
<br>
4. &quot;Semi-OOC&quot; has come up before with bad results to inter-player relationships. What you are suggesting seems to be entirely IC to me and should be swayed by character opinions and agendas, not some concept of fairness. In this way, intrigue and politics become the focus.<br>
<br>
5. Losing status is easy if a Kindred isn't careful (which is why the harpies aren't killed outright, they carry the power to instantly erase years of work). Gaining status is tough. LotN (or the Cam) mentions 1 positive status per story and unlimited status loss, and I would reaffirm the importance of that. A story, as far as I can tell, usually takes longer than a month.<br>
<br>
6. Cam cities are not &quot;nice.&quot; Elders are all the same, no matter sect. Vampire society never seeks to make a leader, only individual vampires do. The status system was developed much like the sects; to keep the powerful powerful and to keep the younger vampires under their sires' fingers. As such, it does not support a strong leader intrinsically, in fact almost the opposite. A strong leader uses the system to their own advantage and bends and creates rules that suit them in such a way that the other vampires in the area don't get upset.<br>
<br>
7. Reacting to status like &quot;Eerie Presence.&quot; I disagree. A player may use one dot of their character's Politics ability to determine the status traits of ONE vampire whose name they know. This means that most vampires do not have their city's population's status memorized unless status was not given out like water. If it took years to gain status, then everyone (all 6 or 7 Kindred in a normal-sized domain) would be able to keep track. On the other hand, I think any neonate who's had more than a few months of training would know exactly how much status is a currency, though maybe not what it is worth.<br>
<br>
8. Just to be clear, I don't think status has anything to do with personality neccessarily. Assuming that status, the currency of vampiric meetings, represents acknowledgement of social charm and character strengths implies that it is these things which are most valuable to vampires. If this were the case, the Sabbat would not exist, nor the anarchs, the Assamites, etc. etc. What is most important to a vampire is far darker and is generally feeding and staying in control. These two things are threatened by every other vampire in the same city, which is where status comes in. It is a way for vampires to deal with each other on vampiric terms, not a judgement of how cool Ken's shoes are (very cool, I would add).<br>
<br>
